</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="18FD1A9EFF895243FF1C1E460850FE11" pageId="15" pageNumber="38" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="50584915FF895243FF1C1E460850FE11" blockId="15.[151,1437,152,487]" pageId="15" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis id="62939507FF895243FF1C1E460A60FED3" bold="true" box="[198,326,267,293]" pageId="15" pageNumber="38">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This genus differs from other 
<taxonomicName id="97E73296FF895243FD3C1E410846FED0" box="[742,864,268,294]" class="Insecta" family="Lucanidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Lucanidae</taxonomicName>
in the following combination of characters: antennomeres of the club mostly glabrous; elytra densely, uniformly punctate (not striate); elytral vestiture consisting of discal spots of scales, spots occasionally coalesced into bands; male with weakly bifurcate pronotal horn anteromedially; horn extending over head; male mandibles more or less triangular, serrate, with peg-like teeth internally, lacking ventral row of setae; male genitalia with capsule simple, everted internal sac straplike with bulbous tip and flagellum (Fig. 
<number id="E62F5B32FF895243FD681E8009E5FE11" box="[690,707,461,487]" pageId="15" pageNumber="38" value="6.0">6</number>
); fully winged.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
